data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3+ supports **strongly-typed `DynamicData`** using `Tuple`-based overloads, and MSTest v4 introduces `[TestDataSource<T>]`. Here are the modern approaches:

**MSTest v3 — Typed `DynamicData`:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

The `DynamicData` attribute in MSTest v3 can resolve `IEnumerable<ValueTuple<...>>` directly — no `object[]` boxing needed.

**MSTest v4 — `[TestDataSource<T>]` (strongest typing):**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestDataSource<TestCases>]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

internal class TestCases : ITestDataSource<(string Input, bool Expected)>
{
    public IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> GetData()
        => [("valid@email.com", true), ("invalid", false), ("", false)];

    public string? GetDisplayName((string Input, bool Expected) data)
        => $"Input: {data.Input}";
}
```

**Key benefits:**
- Compile-time type checking (no runtime `InvalidCastException`)
- Better IDE intellisense on the data properties
- No boxing of value types

The tuple approach (MSTest v3) is the simplest upgrade from your current code.
